                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15292017" author="olegk" created="Thu, 19 May 2016 19:47:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;James&lt;br/&gt;
Are you sure this is a bug? #matchDomainRoot method is package private. Callers of this method are expected to pass normalized host and domainRoot as input.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oleg&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15292062" author="knowever" created="Thu, 19 May 2016 20:18:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Well if I understand what you are saying, you wish the bug to be moved further up in the stack because it should be normalized prior. Which is fine, where do you think it should be normalized?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;org.apache.hc.client5.http.methods.HttpGet() is where it comes in. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So some where between HttpGet method and matchDomainRoot method? &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15293058" author="olegk" created="Fri, 20 May 2016 09:19:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Input parameters should be validated and normalized by public methods whose input the library has no control over. In case of DefaultHostnameVerifier argument validation and normalization should most likely be done by #verify methods.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oleg &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15293145" author="knowever" created="Fri, 20 May 2016 10:39:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Excellent I will be looking forward to being notified when the bug is fixed so I can re-test it.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15293151" author="olegk" created="Fri, 20 May 2016 10:44:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;James,&lt;br/&gt;
What is &lt;em&gt;exactly&lt;/em&gt; the bug you expect me to fix? Would you submit a test case demonstrating it?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oleg&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15293616" author="knowever" created="Fri, 20 May 2016 16:09:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;hmm it might be a few, I am trying to come up with an example that is exposed to public that you can get to, so I am searching for a site with CN in cert the same way&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15305480" author="olegk" created="Sat, 28 May 2016 17:06:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I am still not entirely sure what exactly the reported bug was but I added code to normalize hostname and CN extracted certificate subject when matching to CN.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oleg &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
